AUDIO: 'skills behind the scenes. Skills are not a niche power user feature. They are the layer that turns a general assistant into a specialist who already knows your job. So, let me show you how'

[06:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to build your first one. It is genuinely about 5 minutes. Here\'s the entire thing, start to finish. A skill is just a folder with one file inside it called skill.md. In Claude code, you make a folder in'

[06:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your home directory {dot} Claude/skills/ then your skills name. Inside skill.md, you write a tiny header, a description of what the skill does and when to use it.'

[06:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That one line is what Claude reads to decide when to fire it. And then below it, your actual instructions in plain English. That\'s it. Let me make it real. Say you want Claude to summarize your'

[07:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'code changes. Your description says, "Use this when the user asks what changed or wants a commit message." Then in the body,'

[07:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you can even inject live data. A line that runs git diff and drops the result straight in. Followed by "Summarize these changes in three bullets'

[07:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and flag anything risky." Save it. Now, you either just ask "What did I change?" and Claude loads it automatically, or you type {slash} the skills name to run it on demand. Personal skills'

[07:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'live in dot Claude / skills. Project skills go in the repo. So your whole team shares them. On Claude.ai, you can upload a skill as a simple zip file.'

